    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="616"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d616">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 <gloss target="#t_EW1">E.
                    W.</gloss>/6–2545</note>
                <head>No. 616<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Acting Secretary of State</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]<note n="1" xml:id="d616fn1">For other
                            extracts from this memorandum, see <ref target="#d99">documents Nos.
                                99</ref>, <ref target="#d357">357</ref>, and <ref target="#d637"
                                >637</ref>.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-25">June 25,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum of Conversation</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Subject: United States–French Relations</p>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Participants:</cell>
                        <cell>The French Ambassador, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BH1">Henri
                                Bonnet</persName>;</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell/>
                        <cell>Acting Secretary, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GJC1"
                            >Grew</persName>.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>The Ambassador then said that while he had no instruction from his Government he
                    wished in his capacity as Ambassador responsible for the good relations between
                    our two countries to express to me his concern at the present unfortunate trend
                    of these relations. He said that it was the earnest desire of <persName
                        corresp="#p_DGC1">General de Gaulle</persName> and, as I well knew, of
                    himself to bring France and the United States steadily closer together and he
                    felt that the present trend is unfortunately in the other direction. This arises
                    from a number of issues in which France has been given little satisfaction and
                    public opinion in his country, knowing of these issues, is at present developing
                    in a way not conducive to the improvement of our relations.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>The third point is the fact that although an understanding was reached in the
                    talks which Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BG1">Bidault</persName>, when he was in
                    Washington, had had with President <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName>
                    and myself<note n="2" xml:id="d616fn2">With respect to the scope of the
                            <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_BG1"
                            >Bidault</persName> conversations of May 1945, see Department of State
                            <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xii</hi>, p.
                        927.</note> that a French Army Corps should be permitted to proceed to the
                    Far East to participate in the war against <persName corresp="#p_J1"
                        >Japan</persName>, nothing further had been heard about the matter.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">oseph</hi>] C. G[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >rew</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
